Is Beauty Really Subjective?¶

By Shiv Medler, Luke Luo, Kevin Tang and approved by Professor Morawski

Motivation¶

Humans can recognize beauty instantly, even babies see beauty. However, it is difficult to identify what specifically makes someone beautiful or not beautiful. Why are some features desirable but others are not? We know that there are subjective preferences rooted in culture. Some may generalize these preferences into western and eastern beauty standards. For this project, we will try to see if there are any universal features of beauty.

One data source that we can use for this study is the Chicago Face Database. This database is a folder that contains about 600 images of faces from the United States. These faces include men and women of white, latin, asian, and black descent. For each of these faces, there are corresponding measurements of different attributes of the face alongside subjective ratings of the face based on a U.S. voter sample. We will do regression on the attribute measurements and deep learning on the face images to see if the machine can find variables that explain the variation in the subjective ratings of the faces. If these kinds of variables exist, then we know that there are objective factors to beauty.

One application of this study lies in the face's ability to indicate the health of the individual. Features like acne are unattractive because irregularities in skin usually indicate disease like smallpox or chickenpox. Some features indicate underlying conditions like fetal alcohol syndrome, whose characteristics can be recognized in children. The idea that attractiveness implies health and unattractiveness implies lack of health lends itself to an application for the beauty algorithm. It could be used to detect certain features that suggest diseases and conditions early on.

Furthermore, we know that beauty measurement algorithms are prevalent in today's social media apps, particularly tiktok, where more attractive content creators are pushed to users' recommendations. Nonetheless, these algorithms are used because they attract users' attention. More attention drives more ad revenue, more ad revenue drives more profits for social media companies. The beauty algorithm is just one tool used in recommendation systems. Therefore, through our dataset, we can gain insight into these systems.

Part 1: Linear Regression¶

Method¶

In this part, we will be analyzing the objectivity of beauty by doing linear regression of the facial measurements in the Chicago Face Database. This regression will be done using the statsmodel ordinary least squares method. The method finds the line of best fit by finding a line that minimizes the squared error. More information on the statsmodel OLS linear regression method can be found in this journal.

Data Collection/Storage¶

The data for the subjective ratings of beauty and the facial measurements are all present in the folder excel file. The sheet for the dataset that we are working with is called CFD U.S. Norming Data. A picture of the sheet is shown in the link below:

The issue now is with the column names since the names of the columns were distributed across two rows. This leaves us with three distinct possibilites:

  1. The column name is only present in the dataframe column name and the first row of that column is marked as not a number.

  2. The actual column name is present in the first row of the column and the column name in the dataframe.

  3. The pandas dataframe column name is marked as unnamed while the actual name is in the first row of the column data.

#In the code below, qw renamed the pandas dataframe taking into account these three cases. We did this by creating the new_names dictionary and iterating 
#through the column name and data in the dataframe using the pandas iteritems method. This is because the pandas rename takes in a dictionary with the old 
#names being assigned to the new ones. For the first case, we kept the old name. With the second case, we concantenated the name and the string value for 
#the first row in the column. For the third case, we set the new column to the first row of the column. The result of this renaming is shown below.
new_names = {}

for (columnName, columnData) in face_df.iteritems():
  if pd.isna(columnData[0]):
    new_names[columnName] = columnName
  else:
    if columnName.split(":")[0] == "Unnamed":
      new_names[columnName] = columnData[0]
    else:
      new_names[columnName] = columnName + " " + str(columnData[0])

face_df = face_df.rename(columns = new_names)

Variable Selection¶

For the purposes of this project, we will be focusing on how the measured attributes of the peoples' faces would affect whether people would view them as attractive. Hence, in accordance to the lookup table, we would first look for the column labels that have a corresponding VarID that begins with P. These will be our predictors. Then, we will use Attractive R013_mean as the response variable. The variables measures on average, from a scale of 1-7, how a sample of Americans rated a face as attractive.

The major measurements we lose from selecting the predictors in this way would be the perceptions of the people rating the faces in terms of attractiveness. An example would be the perception of race and gender of a given face for the people rating the face. However, since we are focusing on the unconscious features that people can focus on in assessing a person's beauty, we are not going to look at these features that people were consciously thinking about when assessing the face's attractiveness. Another measurement we would not include would be the size of the sample of people that rated the faces' attractiveness. This is because we believe that these sample sizes were roughly the same in which this information would not be useful in describing the variation for attractiveness. Finally, we are also not looking at the gender and race of the individual since according to the description of Attractive R013-mean, the participants were asked to rate people's face with respect to other people of the same race and gender. Hence, these two variables were controlled for in the data collection process.

To remove the unwanted variables, we used the lookup table shown before in which we intended to use the column's associated VarID in deciding to delete them. Model was removed since it had no corresponding VarID in the table and was not needed since it only stored the filename for a given photo. Before we dropped the columns, however, we sectioned out the Model and Attractiveness columns of the dataframe for the deep learning part of the project.

Addressing Multicollinearity¶

One issue that is present with these variables is multicollinearity. This is where the predictor variables are correlated with each other. This can cause high variance in the estimated coefficients for these variables and lead to misleading interpretations of the regression results. As seen with the column names, there are variables like the measurements of the eye width and height that would seem to be correlated. To see if any of the variables cause this issue, we would look at the Variance Influence Factor values for them. These values are calculated for each predictor by seeing how much of the variation in this predictor is explained by the rest of these predictors.

More information on Multicollinearity and VIF is explained in this link.

In [13]:
#X_variables holds all the measurement predictors for the model which is why the Attractive variable was dropped to form it.
X_variables = face_df.drop(['Attractive R013_mean'],axis=1)
In [14]:
#For the calculate_vif function, the add_constant method from statsmodels is first used since when fitting the linear regression, we plan to include a 
#constant term such that the line can better fit the data. Then, a new dataframe is created in which the feature column would hold the column names while 
#the VIF column would hold the corresponding VIF values. The VIF was calculated by using the variance_inflation_factor method from statsmodel which takes 
#in a dataset of explanatory variables and an index to calculate a VIF value for a given variable. In the code below, this value is calculate for all the 
#indices in the column and stored in a list. This list is then used as the column data for the VIF column. The resulting dataframe is then returned.
def calculate_vif(X):
  X = add_constant(X)
  vif_data = pd.DataFrame()
  vif_data["feature"] = X.columns
  vif_data["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(X.values, i) for i in range(len(X.columns))]
  return vif_data

The output of the calculate_vif function on the X_variables is shown below. A VIF value over 10 indicates multicollinearity in which the variation in that variable can be significantly explained by another explanatory variable. As seen in the output, all of the variables have VIF values above 10. Hence, more variable preprocessing needs to be done to address this effect.

#To select the variables, we iterated through the columns and appending each variable to the final columns list. A local dataframe is constructed with the 
#new_df variable by specifying the variables in this list when accessing the X_variables dataframe. When a new variable is added, if this causes one of the
#variables to have a VIF value of over 10, then this variable is removed and will not be a part of the final_columns list. In the VIF value condition, iloc
#is used since we will only look at the VIF values for the explanatory variables rather than including the constant. The final_columns list is then 
#outputted and shows the columns that were able to be included in the model without having one of the explanatory values have a VIF value above 10.
final_columns = []
for col in X_variables.columns:
  final_columns.append(col) 
  new_df = X_variables[final_columns]
  vif_results = calculate_vif(new_df)

  if vif_results["VIF"].iloc[1:].max() > 10:
    final_columns.remove(col)

Fitting Model/Exploratory Data Analysis¶

In this code below, we fit the selected variables above into the statsmodel ordinary least squares linear model and then printed out the summart of this model. Looking at the R-squared in the summary, we can see that our facial measurement predictors explain 24.2% of the variation in the attractiveness ratings. For real world data, this is a promising result suggesting that the facial measurements that we looked at had an influence on how the different groups rated a face in terms of attractiveness. More information on R-squares is shown here.

As part of the analysis for the linear regression model, we would need to check whether our model meets the assumptions of a linear model. These assumptions include that the errors in the model are normally distributed, independent, have an average of zero (linearity assumption), and have a constant variance. If any of these assumptions are violated, then variable transformation may be needed. The assumptions need to be met such that more valid conclusions can be drawn from the results of the linear model. A fifth assumption is that there is no multicollinearity among the predictors, but we have already addressed this in a previous step. More information about a linear model's assumptions is in this link.

We can check the indepedence, normality, and averages of the error assumption by looking at the residuals vs fitted values scatterplot.

#This is a function that takes in a feature and returns a 2d scatterplot of the
#attractiveness ratings vs this feature. We first set the labels for this graph
#and then get the data for the feature from X. Both this feature and the
#attractiveness ratings are converted into floats such that the line of best

  plt.title("Attractiveness vs " + feature)

  plt.plot(x,y_new, 'yo', x, fn(x), "--k")

We can gain insight into this question by doing hypothesis testing on our model.

Hypothesis Testing: F-Test of Overall Significance¶

To test how well this model fits the data, and whether any of our predictors our significant, an overall F-test can be done. The null hypothesis for this test is that all of the coefficients associated with the predictors in the model are zero. This would mean that none of the predictors would help in explaining the variation in the attractiveness ratings. The alternative hypothesis is that at least one of these coefficients is not equal to zero. This would mean that at least one of the predictors would help in explaining a significant amount of the variation in the attractiveness rating. You can learn more about this kind of hypothesis test in this link.

The F-statistic and its corresponding p-value for the model is given in the OLS summary. These measures are 8.313 and 3.22e-23 respectively. The decision rule in this hypothesis test is whether the p-value is less than alpha in which the standard value for alpha is 0.05. Since 3.22e-23 is less thant 0.05, we would reject the null hypothesis. This means that at least one predictor helps in explaining a significant amount of the variation in the attractiveness ratings. We can gain more insight into the specific predictors that help through partial F-tests.

Hypothesis Testing: Partial F-Test¶

The partial F-test is similar to the F-Test of overall significance in which it tests whether a group of predictors are significant. The null hypothesis and alternative hypothesis are the same in terms of testing whether all of the coefficients are zero or if at least one of them is not equal to zero. However, the different is that the partial test looks at a subset of all of the predictors in the model rather than all of them in terms of testing whether they are significant. This test is done as opposed to doing a series of parameter t-tests since there is a high probability for a type error to occur in at least one of these tests the more that are done in a row. More information about partial F-tests is given here. In the code below, partial F-tests are done in terms of testing the predictors with the lowest t-statistics and corresponding p-values. The tests will be conducted at the 95% level of significance.

In [26]:
#In the function below, threshold represents the minimum p-value that a 
#predictor would have to be to be included in the partial F-test. This means
#that the higher p-values would be tested since these would be the predictors
#denoted as less significant compared to the others. In the code, we iterated
#through all of the predictors and kept an index of them such that we could
#get their p=value through the res.pvalues method. If this p-values was greater
#than or equal to the threshold, it would be included in the hypothesis. This
#means that it would be appended to the hypothesis string as "(predictor = 0),"
#and to the columns list. At the end, the hypothesis string would consist of a
#string with all of the predictors being stated to equal zero in which this
#string can then be inputted into the model results f_test method. From this
#method, the F-statistic and the corresponding p-value of the partial test
#will be printed. The columns list will hold of the predictors used in the
#test and will be returned.
def partial(threshold):
  numberOfAttributes = 22
  hypothesis = ""
  columns = []
  for name, attributeIndex in zip(X.columns, range(1, numberOfAttributes + 1)):
    if res.pvalues[attributeIndex] >= threshold:
      hypothesis += "(" + name + " = 0),"
      columns.append(name)
  hypothesis = hypothesis[:-1]
  f_test = res.f_test(hypothesis)
  print(hypothesis)
  print(f_test)
  return columns

We first did the test with a threshold of 0.025 since these would be the predictors that would have failed the predictor significance two-tailed t-test at a 95% significance level. Looking at the F-statistic and corresponding p-value, since the p-value is less than 0.05, we would reject the null hypothesis. This means that at least one of the predictors tested significantly explained the variation in the attractiveness ratings. Hence, we would be unable to deem the group of predictors as insignifcant.

Summary of Insights for Linear Regression Method¶

There is no general rule to addressing a single feature, ex. not everyone looks better with larger lips. Many rules vary across cultures in which each has their own set of beauty standards. This subjectivity can explain why we saw with our linear regression model that our predictors only explained 20% of the variation in the attractiveness ratings. Furthermore, the lack of general rules can explain why there was no clearly visible linear relationship could be seen in the scatterplots the facial features vs attractiveness ratings. Despite this, the assumptions of the linear model being met alongside the existence of significant predictors suggest that there are certain objective features of beauty.

Part 2: DEEP LEARNING¶

Let's try a different approach this time: Given that we have identified some facial features that are significant in explaining the attractiveness ratings, we will attempt to train a model on the pictures associated with these ratings using Deep Learning to see if we can reach similar conclusions.

Firstly, as a note, it will take much more resources than we have access to in order to train a model from scratch. That is why for this project, we will be outsourcing a pre-initialized image recognition model by using Transfer Learning.

VGG16 is a pre-trained CNN transfer learning framework that has 138 million parameters. It contains a model, VGG_Face, that is tuned for facial recognition. More information about VGG16 can be found here: https://keras.io/api/applications/vgg/

We are going to need the attractiveness scores for each of the models, which brings us back to the deep_df sub-dataframe we sectioned out earlier in the project before we started to drop columns.

Since we're looking for a regression-based classification for the deep learning model, we are going to have to use Mean Squared Error as our loss function. As the optimization function, we will use ADAM to learn slightly faster than gradient descent.

For more information about ADAM and gradient descent updates, feel free to check out this source: https://machinelearningmastery.com/adam-optimization-algorithm-for-deep-learning/#:~:text=Adam%20is%20different%20to%20classical,does%20not%20change%20during%20training.

After compiling with the Adam optimizer, it's time to train the model. Our metric of choice is the validation loss, which is the performance of the model evaluated after every iteration over a subset of data to double-check its efficiency on non-training data.

Along the way, we save a checkpoint of the model, in case we want to load the weights again later.

Additionally, to save time and prevent overfitting, we stop the training once we notice that the validation loss metric has not improved after 10 iterations.

In [41]:

So either the model really loves Cristano Ronaldo or something isn't quite matching up with the model's evaluation on external data sources.

It seems like the model isn't the best at extrapolating "attractiveness scores" of models it hasn't seen before. Despite our best efforts, it seems that overfitting in this scenario is inevitable. First of all, we only trained the model on images of a specific format: No background, 1.44:1 aspect ratio, neutral expression, 50mm focal length.

The pictures of Ronaldo that happened to do well fit this criteria strongly: Centered on the page, more wide than tall, clipping the top of the shoulders.

Even if the model doesn't overfit on features, the restricted nature of the input data itself means that, in general, it doesn't do a good job of accurately rating input that doesn't exactly match. However, it seems like it might still be an estimator of relative attractiveness (Sorry Danny Devito).

CONCLUSION¶

We created a deep learning model and a linear regression model to rate faces. We can say that there are objective measurements that contribute to a higher rating on the linear model. Features like face sizes, nose length, and lip thickness were significant in the linear model. The problem with the linear model is that it measures features independent of other features so there is no concept of balance on a face. Someone could have a nose that is "too large" for their face size but the linear model would not take that into account.

The deep learning model is interesting because there seems to be some merit to its ratings. The images we picked were from searching "person name head shot" on google images to find photos similar to the test data. It could be used to rate images that have the same format relative to each other. Most people would find Cristiano Ronaldo more attractive than Danny Devito (4 > 2). Interestingly, it can also be used to rate animated images of characters like Kevin the Minion and Zhong Li from Genshin Impact (3 > 2.5). Gal Gadot, Zhong Li, and Michael B. Jordan had ratings around a 3 and are considered conventionally attractive. These ratings seem reasonable to us.

It is remarkably difficult to rate attractiveness because the face is more than the sum of its parts. Faces are conventionally attractive when the features go together well. This is difficult for an algorithm to know but easy for a human to spot. Even then, it is hard for people to know why they find someone attractive. There are subjective preferences that change over time, such as beauty trends and cultural standards. On the other hand, there are features that are timeless. There is merit to the argument that beauty is objective. The linear model puts ratings on an individual's feature measurements and takes the sum of its parts. We do not know how the deep learning model rates but that seems to be the case with people in real life. Perhaps it takes the face's balance into account. What we know is that there is some merit to its predictions. After this, we still do not know what makes beautiful faces, we only know the ratings of these faces. Finding what makes faces attractive may be futile as everyone has their own unique preferences.
